'''Evelyn Dearman''' (8 September 1908 – 2 December 1993) was an English female tennis player who was active during the late 1920s and the 1930s.

Between 1927 and 1939 she participated in 13 [[Wimbledon Championships]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Wimbledon players archive – Evelyn Dearman|url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/scores/draws/archive/players/ce596326-eed5-4467-ae42-2afc19601ac3/index.html|publisher=[[AELTC]]}}</ref> Her best result in the singles event was reaching the third round in [[1933 Wimbledon Championships|1933]] and [[1937 Wimbledon Championships|1937]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Wimbledon players archive – Evelyn Dearman – Singles|url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/scores/draws/archive/players/ce596326-eed5-4467-ae42-2afc19601ac3/LS.html|publisher=[[AELTC]]}}</ref> In the doubles event Dearman reached the semifinal in 1937 partnering [[Joan Ingram (tennis)|Joan Ingram]]. That same year she teamed-up with [[Daniel Prenn]] to reach the semifinal of the mixed doubles competition which they lost to the second-seeded pair [[Simonne Mathieu]] and [[Yvon Petra]].

Her biggest success at [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] level came in 1935 when she partnered with [[Nancy Lyle Glover]] to win the doubles title at the [[1935 Australian Championships]], defeating [[Louie Bickerton]] and [[Nell Hall Hopman]] in the final in straight sets.<ref>{{cite web|title=Australian Open players results archive – Evelyn Dearman|url=http://www.ausopen.com/en_AU/event_guide/history/players/6451.html|publisher=Tennis Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Collins|first=Bud|title=The Bud Collins History of Tennis|year=2010|publisher=New Chapter Press|location=[New York]|isbn=978-0942257700|page=373|edition=2nd}}</ref> 

In July 1931 she won the singles title at the [[Canadian Championships]] after a walkover in the final against compatriot [[Mary Hardwick]].<ref name=robertson>{{cite book|last=Robertson|first=Max|title=The Encyclopedia of Tennis|year=1974|publisher=Allen & Unwin|location=London|isbn=9780047960420|page=215}}</ref>  With Hardwick she also won the doubles title.<ref>{{cite web|title=Past Champions & Draws|url=http://www.rogerscup.com/women/english/pastChampionsAndDraws.php|publisher=Tennis Canada|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140423105318/http://www.rogerscup.com/women/english/pastChampionsAndDraws.php|archivedate=23 April 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> From 1934 until 1937 Dearman was part of the British [[Wightman Cup]] team as a doubles player. These four editions were won by the United States.

